1000.name: canDeviceType
1000.desc: The object at index 1000h describes the type of device and its functionality. It is composed of a 16-bit field which describes the device profile that is used and a second 16-bit field which gives additional information about optional functionality of the device. The Additional Information parameter is device profile specific.

1001.name: canErrorRegister
1001.desc: This object is an error register for the device. The device can map internal errors in this byte. This entry is mandatory for all devices. It is a part of an Emergency object.

1005.name: canSync
1005.desc: Index 1005h defines the COB-ID of the Synchronisation Object (SYNC). Further, it defines whether the device generates the SYNC.

1006.name: canCommunicationCyclePeriod
1006.desc: This object defines the communication cycle period in  s. This period defines the SYNC interval. It is 0 if not used. If the communication cycle period on sync producer is changed to a new value unequal 0 the transmission of sync object resumes within 1 sync cycle of the new value.

1009.name: canManufacturerDeviceVersion
1009.desc: Contains the manufacturer hardware version description.

100A.name: canManufacturerSoftwareVersion
100A.desc: Contains the manufacturer software version description

100C.name: canGuardTime
100C.desc: The objects at index 100Ch and 100Dh include the guard time in milliseconds and the life time factor. The life time factor multiplied with the guard time gives the life time for the Life Guarding Protocol. It is 0 if not used.

100D.name: canLifeTimeFactor
100D.desc: The life time factor multiplied with the guard time gives the life time for the node guarding protocol. It is 0 if not used.

1010.name: canStoreParameters
1010.desc: This object supports the saving of parameters in non volatile memory. By read access the device provides information about its saving capabilities. Several parameter groups are distinguished: Sub-Index 0 contains the largest Sub-Index that is supported. Sub-Index 1 refers to all parameters that can be stored on the device. Sub-Index 2 refers to communication related parameters (Index 1000h - 1FFFh manufacturer specific communication parameters). Sub-Index 3 refers to application related parameters (Index 6000h - 9FFFh manufacturer specific application parameters). At Sub-Index 4 - 127 manufacturers may store their choice of parameters individually. Sub-Index 128 - 254 are reserved for future use.

1011.name: canRestoreDefaultParameters
1011.desc: With this object the default values of parameters according to the communication or device profile are restored. By read access the device provides information about its capabilities to restore these values. Several parameter groups are distinguished: Sub-Index 0 contains the largest Sub-Index that is supported. Sub-Index 1 refers to all parameters that can be restored. Sub-Index 2 refers to communication related parameters (Index 1000h - 1FFFh manufacturer specific communication parameters). Sub-Index 3 refers to application related parameters (Index 6000h - 9FFFh manufacturer specific application parameters). At Sub-Index 4 - 127 manufacturers may restore their individual choice of parameters. Sub-Index 128 - 254 are reserved for future use.

1012.name: canTimeStampMessage
1012.desc: Index 1012h defines the COB-ID of the Time-Stamp Object (TIME). Further, it defines whether the device consumes the TIME or whether the device generates the TIME.

1013.name: canHighResolutionTimeStamp
1013.desc: This object contains a time stamp with a resolution of 1  s. It can be mapped into a PDO in order to define a high resolution time stamp message. (Note that the data type of the standard time stamp message (TIME) is fixed). Further application specific use is encouraged.

1014.name: canEmergencyMessage
1014.desc: Index 1014h defines the COB-ID of the Emergency Object (EMCY).

1015.name: canInhibitTimeEmcy
1015.desc: The inhibit time for the EMCY message can be adjusted via this entry. If this entry exists it must be writable in the object dictionary. The time has to be a multiple of 100 s.

1017.name: canProducerHeartbeatTime
1017.desc: The producer hartbeat time defines the cycle time of the heartbeat. The producer heartbeat time is 0 if it not used. The time has to be a multiple of 1ms.

1018.name: Identity_Object
1018.desc: The object at index 1018h contains general information about the device. The no of entries (sub-index 0h) is always 4. The Vendor ID (sub-index 1h) contains a unique value allocated to each manufacturer. The manufacturer-specific Product code (sub-index 2h) identifies a specific device version. The manufacturer-specific Revision number (sub-index 3h) consists of a major revision number and a minor revision number. The major revision number identifies a specific CANopen behaviour. If the CANopen functionality is expanded, the major revision has to be incremented. The minor revision number identifies different versions with the same CANopen behaviour. The serial number (sub index 04h) contains the serial number of the product in the BDR standard.

1029.name: canErrorBehaviour
1029.desc: If a serious device failure is detected in Operational State, the module shall enter by default autonomously the pre-operational state. If object 1029h (Error Behaviour) is implemented, the device can be configured to enter alternatively the stopped state or remain in the current state in case of a device failure. Device failures shall include the following communication errors:   Bus-off conditions of the CAN interface   Life guarding event with the state  occurred    Heartbeat event with state  occurred  Severe device errors also can be caused by device internal failures.

1200.name: canServerSdoParameter
1200.desc: In order to describe the SDOs used on a device the data type SDO Parameter is introduced. The data type has the index 22h in the Object Dictionary. The structure is described in 9.5.4. The number of supported entries in the SDO object record is specified at sub-index 0h. The values at 1h and 2h specify the COB-ID for this SDO. Sub-index 3 gives the server of the SDO in case the record describes an SDO for which the device is client and gives the client of the SDO if the record describes an SDO for which the device is server.

1280.name: canClientSdoParameter0
1280.desc: These objects contain the parameters for the SDOs for which the device is the client. If the entry is supported, all sub-indices must be available. Starting at index 1280h and subsequent indices. The entries are described at the Server SDO Parameter.

1281.name: canClientSdoParameter1
1281.desc: These objects contain the parameters for the SDOs for which the device is the client. If the entry is supported, all sub-indices must be available. Starting at index 1280h and subsequent indices. The entries are described at the Server SDO Parameter.

1282.name: canClientSdoParameter2
1282.desc: These objects contain the parameters for the SDOs for which the device is the client. If the entry is supported, all sub-indices must be available. Starting at index 1280h and subsequent indices. The entries are described at the Server SDO Parameter.

1F02.name: canSdoManagerCobIds
1F02.desc: For establishing dynamic SDO connection the SDO Manager requires information about the COB-IDs that are free in the system. This can be configured in object 1F02.

1F10.name: canDynamicSdoConnectionState
1F10.desc: This object is used for the SRD registration process as well as for the confirmation of an established SDO connection to a device S which the SRD has requested by the SDO Manager before.

1F11.name: canSlaveFailed
1F11.desc: This object dictionary entry is used to inform the SRD that the slave S caused a Error Control Error Event. The dynamic SDO connection is not longer valid. The Manager starts automatically to release the dynamic SDO connection. This object is optional on the SRD and is only supported if the Manager supports bit 3 in object 1F10h (Dynamic SDO Connection State).

1F80.name: canNmtStartup
1F80.desc: This object configures the start-up behaviour of a device that is able to perform the NMT.

1F81.name: canSlaveAssignment
1F81.desc: This object assigns slaves to the NMT Master. It gives information about Error Control Parameters and about actions to be performed on Error Control Events. All other parameters according to a slave in the Network List are only valid, if the slave is assigned to the SlaveAssignment 1F81h

1F85.name: canVendorIdentification
1F85.desc: This object allows to enter values for expected Vendor IDs. Sub-Index 00h has the value of the highest node ID that was given out by the master. Each Sub-Index in the array corresponds to the slave with the Node ID equal to the SubIndex. The Sub-Index equal to the Master s Node-ID is ignored. If a value in this array is not 0, on boot-up procedure the Master will read object 1018h, Sub-Index 01h of the device and compare it to the actual value. The Boot-Up for that device is only continued on exact equality. The application may perform additional checks   e.g. for serial numbers.

1F86.name: canProductCode
1F86.desc: 1F86h ProductCode: List of expected ProductCode (Object 1018h Sub-Index 02h) for each expected slave device. Sub-Index 00h has the value 127d. Each sub-index in the array correspond to the slave with the Node-ID equal to the sub-index. If a value in this array is not 0, on Boot-Up procedure the Master will read object 1018h, Sub-Index 02h of the device and compare it to the actual value, and the Boot-Up for that device is only continued on exact equality.

1F87.name: canRevisionNumber
1F87.desc: 1F87h RevisionNumber: List of expected RevisionNumber (Object 1018h Sub-Index 03h) for each expected slave device. Sub-Index 00h has the value 127d. Each sub-index in the array correspond to the slave with the Node-ID equal to the sub-index. If a value in this array is not 0, on Boot-Up procedure the Master will read object 1018h, Sub-Index 03h of the device and compare it to the actual value. As revision number include major and minor revision, the BootUp for that device is only continued on "exact mach" on the major revision and "greater than" on minor revision number.

1F88.name: canSerialNumber
1F88.desc: 1F88h SerialNumber: List of expected SerialNumber (Object 1018h Sub-Index 04h) for each expected slave device. Sub-Index 00h has the value 127d. Each sub-index in the array correspond to the slave with the Node-ID equal to the sub-index. If a value in this array is not 0, on Boot-Up procedure the Master will read object 1018h, Sub-Index 04h of the device and compare it to the actual value, and the Boot-Up for that device is only continued on exact equality

200D.name: parApDeviceInfoBootLoaderVersion

200E.name: parApLocale

200F.name: parApTimeNTPupdateEnabled
